5.body:
When I came into the web3 security space, I was already researching this area with the plan of doing a startup. So I was constantly familiarizing myself with blockchain technologies and focussing on the development aspect. Prior to that I was what you call a "security enthusiast" in the web2 (traditional centralized computing) domain. The web3 space during that period was under constant exploitation, with astronomical sums being lost. This was the impetus that led me down this rabbit hole. %%{init: {'theme':'dark'}}%%
flowchart TD A[<font size=22px> WHS <br> plan <br>]-->B(Learn<br>Fundamentals ) A --> C(Attempt<br>CTFS) A --> D(Attempt<br>Bounties) B --> b1(Solidity<br>Fundamentals) B --> b2(Javascript<br>Fundamentals) C --> c1(Ongoing<br>On my<br>Github Repo) click c1 href "https://github.com/m0ham3dx/mxweb3ctfs" "M0ham3dx Github Repo" _blank D --> d1(Attempts on programs <br> To be documented) The above map was my own take on this matter after researching several learning paths. The good news was that the area of web3 Security was already heavily under investigation. This led to a wide variety of information which was available online. My primary research reference was w3bs3c - Compilation of Web3 Security .

6.body:
The following methodology was arrived at after researching existing web2 & web3 methodologies. %%{init: {'theme':'dark'}}%%
flowchart TD %% Header box MX(<font size=20px>m0ham3dx<br>WHS BB Methodology) o--oA style MX stroke-width:0px %% Phase 1 A[My<br>Methodology<br>Evolving]-->B(Phase 1 <br> Recon) B --> B1(Lookover Immunefi BB <br> Glance at main wesbite) B --Prevent<br>Examining known<br>Problems --> B2(Review<br>Existing<br>Audit Reports ) %% Phase 2 A --> C(Phase 2<br>Automated<br>Testing) C --> C1(Solidity<br>) C1 --> C11(Slither ) C1 --> C12(Mythril ) C --> C2(Rust<br>) C2 --Rust Code<br> Being Learnt --> C21( -Soteria<br> -CargoFuzz ) %% Phase 3 Identify Vulnerbale Function Boxes A --> D(Phase 3<br> Identify Functions<br> prone to being exploited ) D --Automated --> D1(Solidity<br>Metrics ) D --Manual --> D2(Read<br>Contract ) %% Phase 4 - Threat Modeling A --> E(Phase 4<br>Threat<br>Modelling ) E --> E1(Examine previous<br>vulnerabilities <br> based on type<br>of contract ) E1 --Classic<br>Threat Hunting<br>Method <br>--> E2{{1. Identify Entry Points <br> 2. Determine Threat Scenarios <br> 3. Determine Actors }} click E href "https://www.w3bs3c.com/list?recordId=recWW7im5o9S9uaDF" _blank %% Phase 5 Fuzzing A --> F(Phase 5<br>Fuzzing ) F --> F1(Echidna<br>) F --> F2(Foundry<br>) click F2 href "https://book.getfoundry.sh/forge/fuzz-testing.html" _blank %% Phase 6 A --> G(Phase 6 <br> POC ) subgraph Submission G --> G1(Write Unit Tests<br>to prove POC ) G1 --> G2(Foundry ) click G2 href "https://book.getfoundry.sh/forge/writing-tests.html" _blank G1 --> G3(Brownie ) end %% Phase 7 A---H(Phase 7 <br> Fix ) H-->H1(Participate with project <br> for recommending fix ) The summary of the above diagram is as follows : Phase 1 - Recon - Which means gathering information about your target, this phase is considered to be the most important phase in this process, poor recon leads to inability to identify bugs. Phase 2 - Automated Testing - This is often used for baselining . Usually most projects already use automated testing in their testing pipelines. However as the code base gets constantly updated, the probability of logical errors go up, and automated tooling is a fast way (albeit not the most precise way, due to the presence of false positives). Phase 3 - Exploitable Functions - This step involves functions that are prone to being exploited , some eg: of arbitray functions - depositFunds() - Crypto IN withdrawFunds() - Crypto OUT Hint 游녤 Smart Contract Weakness Classification Registry (SCWCR) - A repository of known vulnerability issues in Ethereum - Not updated regularly. Phase 4 - Threat Modelling - Once vulnerable code has been identified, the next step is to assess the risk of those functions in simulated conditions. As a good starting point, it was recommended to read about past attacks via bug reports such as those listed in the Immunefi Blog , that give technical details on how the exploit occurred. Info 游녤 The three core levels of thinking for a Bug Hunter - Excellent tweet thread on threat modelling methodology . Phase 5 - Fuzzing - Accomplished by tooling that can rapidly input a wide range of inputs to assess the behavior of a function. Note - This step is not necessarily agreed upon, but in my opinion is a fast way to assess the risk of a bug which has been identified. Phase 6 - POC - A critical step in making the project understand the impact of the finding. This step is often overlooked either due to negligence or lack of technical ability, to write a great POC . The latter issue can be rectified by learning how existing POC's for findings have been written. This step is crucial in determining a payout.

8.body: Language Upskilling - The most commonly used development languages are : Solidity- Target -> EVM - Vast majority of blockchain projects or DAPPS are on the Ethereum Chain. Rust -> Solana / Near - Rust in addition to being a popular language for general development, since it is the closest to the C language, is also used for blockchain apps development. Javascript - Solidity is close to javascript and tests written for solidity dapps are in javascript which are used by the Hardhat - Popular Development Environment for Dapp Development . However at the time of writing this report, there is a much faster Solidity Development Environment which has been written entirely in rust from the ground up. Its name is Foundry , one big advantage of this tool is that all the tests are written in solidity Pythonic Languages - Vyper , Brownie & Apeworks are all pythonic languages, which are used for dapp development and testing. Perfect for all the pythonista's. Example 游녤 Plot showing languages used for blockchain development. Tooling - There are a variety of tools that make the testing of smart contract code a whole lot easier. They can be grouped into the following categories. Some tools have multiple functions. These are just the ones which I use and/or have come across. Transactions Analyzers Eththx Transaction Decoders Tenderly Dashboard Dedaub Automated Exploit Scanners Slither Mythril Fast Development Environments Foundry Tenderly Fuzzers Echidna Foundry Hint 游녤 More tools can be founder here - W3bS3C - Auditing and Development Tools CTF's - There exists a variety of CTF's for web3. I am actively attempting on some of them HERE. Note 游녤 As of writing this report there is a second version of the famous Paradigm CTF, which is scheduled between 2022-08-20T00:00:00.000Z to 2022-08-22T00:00:00.000Z HERE.
